<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<project xmlns="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         xsi:schemaLocation="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0 https://maven.apache.org/xsd/maven-4.0.0.xsd">
  <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>

  <!--
    Chapter 29 companion (A Build You Can Stand Behind). The chapter's subject is the BUILD itself and the
    dependency tree it assembles — making the artifact reproducible (bit-for-bit identical from the same
    source) and the tree's licenses known and within policy. So this module's load-bearing artifact is THIS
    pom.xml and the config files beside it, not the small Java package. The pom carries both facets as real
    build configuration:

      * Technical integrity (always on, default build, fully OFFLINE): a fixed
        <project.build.outputTimestamp> normalises JAR-entry and MANIFEST timestamps, and the
        reproducible-build plugin strips the remaining build-time variability (file ordering, manifest
        details) so a rebuild from the same source produces the same bytes.
      * Legal integrity (-Pquality profile, OFFLINE): the license-maven-plugin reads the resolved
        dependency tree's declared licenses, gates on an allow-list (fail the build on a license outside
        policy), and generates a THIRD-PARTY attribution from the same license data.

    A small org.acme.repro package gives the build a real dependency graph to read licenses from and gives
    both facets an in-code analogue a test can drive, so the configuration is exercised, not merely declared.

    SOURCE-PIN: Java 21 anchor (built with openjdk@21 21.0.11; forward-check 25.0.3); Maven 3.9.16; JUnit
    6.x BOM; AssertJ 3.27.7; commons-lang3 pinned (3.18.0, Apache-2.0). The reproducible-build-maven-plugin
    and license-maven-plugin version LITERALS are NOT separately pinned in SOURCE-PIN (the reproducible-
    builds.org / SPDX / license-tools rows are marked TO-PIN), so they are held as named properties and
    flagged — see 09-flags/67_repro_license_plugin_versions_unpinned.md (the same plugin/engine two-pin
    discipline the Checkstyle and Enforcer modules follow). The license content is FACTUAL, NOT LEGAL ADVICE
    (per LEGAL-IP-RULES): the gate reports DECLARED licenses; interpreting obligations needs legal counsel.
  -->
  <parent>
    <groupId>org.acme.storefront</groupId>
    <artifactId>companion-code</artifactId>
    <version>1.0.0-SNAPSHOT</version>
  </parent>

  <artifactId>reproducible-builds-license-compliance</artifactId>
  <name>Chapter 29 — A Build You Can Stand Behind (reproducible-builds-license-compliance)</name>

  <properties>
    <!--
      A fixed build timestamp is the single biggest source of Java non-determinism: without it, every JAR
      entry and the MANIFEST carry the wall-clock time of the build, so two builds of the same source differ
      in their bytes. Maven reads <project.build.outputTimestamp> and stamps every archive entry with this
      fixed value instead (an ISO-8601 instant or a Unix epoch second). Pinned here to a fixed date so a
      rebuild is byte-identical. This is the precondition that makes a provenance attestation (Chapter 28)
      describe a stable thing rather than a moving target.
    -->
    <!-- tag::repro-timestamp[] -->
    <project.build.outputTimestamp>2026-06-20T00:00:00Z</project.build.outputTimestamp>
    <!-- end::repro-timestamp[] -->

    <!--
      Plugin version literals NOT separately pinned in SOURCE-PIN (the reproducible-builds.org / SPDX /
      license-tools rows are TO-PIN). Held as named properties so a single edit re-pins each once the
      SOURCE-PIN row is set, the same two-pin discipline the Checkstyle build-plugin/engine and Enforcer
      splits already follow. Flagged: 09-flags/67_repro_license_plugin_versions_unpinned.md. The values used
      resolve cleanly on the pinned toolchain (Maven 3.9.16, JDK 21.0.11).
    -->
    <reproducible.build.plugin.version>0.17</reproducible.build.plugin.version>
    <license.plugin.version>2.7.1</license.plugin.version>
  </properties>

  <dependencies>
    <!--
      A real, named, PINNED dependency so the license gate has a genuine declared license to read and so the
      generated THIRD-PARTY attribution lists a real component (the chapter's point: license compliance acts
      on the resolved graph, not an empty one). Apache Commons Lang is a widely-used, JDK-only library under
      Apache-2.0 — a permissive license that passes the allow-list and requires only attribution. The version
      is pinned (no range, no LATEST) so the build is reproducible: the deterministic-tree precondition the
      previous chapters established and this chapter depends on.
    -->
    <dependency>
      <groupId>org.apache.commons</groupId>
      <artifactId>commons-lang3</artifactId>
      <version>3.18.0</version>
    </dependency>
    <dependency>
      <groupId>org.junit.jupiter</groupId>
      <artifactId>junit-jupiter</artifactId>
      <scope>test</scope>
    </dependency>
    <dependency>
      <groupId>org.assertj</groupId>
      <artifactId>assertj-core</artifactId>
      <scope>test</scope>
    </dependency>
  </dependencies>

  <!--
    The reproducible-build plugin ALWAYS runs in this module (bound to the default build, not opt-in),
    because the chapter's whole point is that reproducibility is a property of the artifact every build
    produces, not an optional report. It runs fully OFFLINE: it post-processes the JAR Maven already built,
    stripping the residual non-determinism that <project.build.outputTimestamp> alone does not cover (archive
    file ordering, manifest entry order). The honest edge the chapter names holds here: this makes the
    artifact deterministic and verifiable, it says NOTHING about whether the code is correct (a reproducible
    build of buggy code is reliably, verifiably buggy — stated in code in ReproducibleArtifact).
  -->
  <build>
    <plugins>
      <plugin>
        <groupId>io.github.zlika</groupId>
        <artifactId>reproducible-build-maven-plugin</artifactId>
        <version>${reproducible.build.plugin.version}</version>
        <executions>
          <execution>
            <id>strip-jar</id>
            <phase>package</phase>
            <goals>
              <goal>strip-jar</goal>
            </goals>
          </execution>
        </executions>
        <!-- tag::repro-plugin[] -->
        <configuration>
          <!-- the fixed timestamp comes from <project.build.outputTimestamp>; strip-jar strips the rest:
               normalises archive entry order + default manifest stamps (Built-By, Build-Jdk). -->
          <manifestAttributes>
            <manifestAttribute>Build-Timestamp</manifestAttribute>  <!-- strip a custom build-time stamp too -->
          </manifestAttributes>
        </configuration>
        <!-- end::repro-plugin[] -->
      </plugin>
    </plugins>
  </build>

  <!--
    The license gate and the static-analysis gate are opt-in via -Pquality so the default build stays fast.
    Both run fully OFFLINE here (the license plugin reads license metadata from the already-resolved POMs).
    This profile is the green build of record for FLOOR C.
  -->
  <profiles>
    <profile>
      <id>quality</id>
      <build>
        <plugins>
          <!--
            License compliance (the chapter's "know the tree's licenses + stop a banned one shipping +
            produce attributions" answer). The add-third-party goal reads every resolved component's
            DECLARED license, checks it against the externalized allow-list (config/license/allowed-licenses
            .txt, referenced as a file:// URL via <includedLicenses>), FAILS the build on a license outside
            policy (<failOnBlacklist>true), and writes a THIRD-PARTY attribution to target/generated-sources
            /license/THIRD-PARTY.txt — the aggregated NOTICE permissive licenses require, automated from the
            inventory. With only the permissive, Apache-2.0 commons-lang3 on the path, the gate PASSES and
            the attribution lists it. The FAILURE PATH (a banned license fails the build) is shown in code
            (LicensePolicy + DisallowedLicenseException) rather than by seeding a real copyleft dependency,
            which would be non-deterministic and an IP concern. FACTUAL, NOT LEGAL ADVICE.
          -->
          <plugin>
            <groupId>org.codehaus.mojo</groupId>
            <artifactId>license-maven-plugin</artifactId>
            <version>${license.plugin.version}</version>
            <!-- tag::license-gate[] -->
            <configuration>
              <failOnBlacklist>true</failOnBlacklist>   <!-- a license outside the allow-list FAILS the build -->
              <includedLicenses>file://${project.basedir}/config/license/allowed-licenses.txt</includedLicenses>
              <excludedScopes>test</excludedScopes>     <!-- gate what SHIPS: runtime+compile, not test tools -->
              <thirdPartyFilename>THIRD-PARTY.txt</thirdPartyFilename>   <!-- the auto-generated NOTICE -->
            </configuration>
            <!-- end::license-gate[] -->
            <executions>
              <execution>
                <id>license-allow-list-and-notice</id>
                <phase>verify</phase>
                <goals>
                  <goal>add-third-party</goal>
                </goals>
              </execution>
            </executions>
          </plugin>

          <!--
            Static-analysis gate (Chapter 16), same house shape as the other chapter modules: the checkstyle
            build-plugin and its engine are pinned separately (the two-pin lesson), and configs are
            externalized under this module's config/ dir.
          -->
          <plugin>
            <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
            <artifactId>maven-checkstyle-plugin</artifactId>
            <version>3.6.0</version>
            <dependencies>
              <dependency>
                <groupId>com.puppycrawl.tools</groupId>
                <artifactId>checkstyle</artifactId>
                <version>10.26.1</version>
              </dependency>
            </dependencies>
            <configuration>
              <configLocation>config/checkstyle/checkstyle.xml</configLocation>
              <consoleOutput>true</consoleOutput>
              <failOnViolation>true</failOnViolation>
              <violationSeverity>error</violationSeverity>
              <includeTestSourceDirectory>true</includeTestSourceDirectory>
            </configuration>
            <executions>
              <execution>
                <id>checkstyle-check</id>
                <phase>verify</phase>
                <goals>
                  <goal>check</goal>
                </goals>
              </execution>
            </executions>
          </plugin>
          <plugin>
            <groupId>com.github.spotbugs</groupId>
            <artifactId>spotbugs-maven-plugin</artifactId>
            <version>4.9.3.0</version>
            <configuration>
              <effort>Max</effort>
              <threshold>Medium</threshold>
              <includeTests>false</includeTests>
              <excludeFilterFile>config/spotbugs/spotbugs-exclude.xml</excludeFilterFile>
            </configuration>
            <executions>
              <execution>
                <id>spotbugs-check</id>
                <phase>verify</phase>
                <goals>
                  <goal>check</goal>
                </goals>
              </execution>
            </executions>
          </plugin>
        </plugins>
      </build>
    </profile>
  </profiles>
</project>
